SIMPLE: plunder
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Plunder
<hw>Plun"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Plundered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Plundering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[G.
<ets>pl⟦uum⟧ndern</ets> to plunder, <ets>plunder</ets> frippery,
baggage.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To take the goods of by force, or
without right; to pillage; to spoil; to sack; to strip; to rob; <as>as,
to <ex>plunder</ex> travelers</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nebuchadnezzar <qex>plunders</qex> the temple of God.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To take by pillage; to appropriate forcibly; <as>as,
the enemy <ex>plundered</ex> all the goods they found</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To pillage; despoil; sack; rifle; strip;
rob.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plunder</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Plunder
<hw>Plun"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act
of plundering or pillaging; robbery. See <xex>Syn.</xex> of
<er>Pillage</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Inroads and <qex>plunders</qex> of the Saracens.</q> <rj><qau>Sir
T. North.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is taken by open force from an enemy;
pillage; spoil; booty; also, that which is taken by theft or
fraud.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧He shared in the <xex>plunder</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Personal property and effects; baggage or
luggage.</def> <mark>[Slang, Southwestern U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plunderage</ent>⟦br⟧
